    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that helps. u mentioned the spooky action part... is there like a specific reason why it's called that? like why does it feel so weird compared to just regular physics stuff?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"spooky action at a distance\" is indeed a peculiar term, coined by none other than Albert Einstein himself. He used it to express his discomfort and skepticism about the phenomenon of quantum entanglement. Einstein, along with his colleagues Podolsky and Rosen, proposed a thought experiment known as the EPR paradox, which aimed to show that quantum mechanics was incomplete. They argued that if quantum mechanics were correct, it would imply that particles could instantaneously affect each other over vast distances, which seemed to violate the principle of locality — the idea that objects are only directly influenced by their immediate surroundings.\n\nEinstein found this notion \"spooky\" because it defied his classical understanding of the universe, where cause and effect are bound by the speed of light, and nothing can travel faster. In the realm of classical physics, it's hard to imagine how two objects could be connected in such a way that a change in one would instantly affect the other, regardless of the distance separating them. This instantaneous connection seemed to Einstein like a violation of the very fabric of reality as he understood it.\n\nQuantum entanglement, however, has been experimentally confirmed time and again, and it remains one of the most fascinating and mysterious aspects of quantum mechanics.",
      "source": "target",
